$ \begin {aligned} \case (l_i(t), x. u_1, y. u_2) \approx _{\beta } u_i[t/x_i] \\ u[t/y] \approx _{\eta } \case (l_i(t), x. u[l_1(x)/z], y. u[l_2(y)/z]) : C \\ u[t/y] \approx _{\text {weak}-\eta } \case (l_i, x. l_1(x), y. l_2(y)) : C \end {aligned} $

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Paraphrased from n-Lab:
The \eta law says that if we unpack a term of type A + B and then use the resulting term only to repackage it as a term of type A + B, then we can skip the unpacking. We obtain the weak \eta law by specifying the resulting type as A + B and u := z.
This presentation adapts the presentation from here.
